<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-commerical-arithmetic-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Commerical Arithmetic in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Appreciate the use of commercial arithmetic in real-life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To systematically discover the mathematical behavior of simple interest versus reducing balance compound growth, and derive general algebraic expressions for geometric growth scales.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into collaborative task groups and distribute the business scenario. Act as an active facilitator: guide groups to notice that while Plan A adds a static constant amount each cycle, Plan B repeatedly applies a scalar multi-multiplier (<m>1.08</m>) to the changing balance. Prompt teams during further exploration to express repeated multiplication using index notation, guiding them toward the exponential variable structure.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>

            <p>
                <term>Group Investigation Activity</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                In Mombasa County, a group of learners have started a small weekend business selling bottled water and snacks during school events and public gatherings. They notice that their income changes depending on the season, transport costs, and demand from customers.
            </p>

            <p>
                One weekend, they borrow Ksh <m>12,000</m> from a community youth fund to expand their business. The fund manager gives them two repayment plans:
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Plan A:</term> A fixed simple interest rate of <m>8\%</m> per year is charged on the original amount for <m>3</m> years.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Plan B:</term> A reducing balance system is used where interest is charged each year on the updated amount after previous growth is included, at a rate of <m>8\%</m> per year.
            </p>

            <p>
                The group is unsure which plan is fair and sustainable for their business.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>In your groups, investigate:</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <term>Plan A</term>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    Determine the interest charged each year.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Find the total interest after <m>3</m> years.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Determine the total amount to be repaid.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What do you observe about how the interest behaves over time?
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <term>Plan B</term>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    Compute the amount owed at the end of each year.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Determine the total repayment after <m>3</m> years.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What changes each year in this system, and what remains the basis for calculation?
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the two plans:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    Which plan is cheaper for the group in the long run?
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Which plan grows faster over time?
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Which plan would you recommend for a growing business? Give reasons.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Further Exploration</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                The group notices a pattern in Plan B where each year the amount is multiplied by the same factor.
                Investigate how this pattern can be written in a general mathematical form.
            </p>

            <p>
                Use your result to predict:
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        The amount after <m>4</m> years
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The amount after <m>5</m> years
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The amount after <m>n</m> years
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Reflection</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                Discuss in your group:
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        How does mathematics help in making financial decisions in real life situations?
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Why is it important for business owners to understand different growth patterns of money?
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize algebraic variations between linear addition structures and exponential growth or decay models.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Use findings from the learner group reports to formally contrast the base accumulation profiles. Write the progression rules explicitly on the board: show that simple interest acts as an arithmetic progression adding a constant dividend (<m>I = \frac{PRT}{100}</m>), whereas reducing compound scales utilize recurring geometric factor transformations (<m>A = P(1 + \frac{R}{100})^n</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Multiplier Concept:</alert> Anchor the concept of percentage growth and decay multipliers. Show that an <m>8\%</m> interest rate translates to an appreciation multiplier of <m>1.08</m>, while a <m>20\%</m> technical depreciation rate simplifies to a value retention factor of <m>0.80</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Real-World Contextual:</alert> Warn learners about the true nature of financial options. Point out that while hire purchase agreements or mobile loan platforms are convenient, they often hide high effective interest rates compared to regular local savings co-operatives (SACCOs).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            
                <term>Exploring Growth of Money in Real Life</term>
        </p>

                <p>
                    From the group investigation, learners observed that money can grow in different ways depending on the financial system used.
                    Some systems increase the amount steadily, while others grow faster over time.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Observing Simple Growth</term>
                </p>

                    <p>
                        In Plan A, the interest is calculated on the original amount only.
                        This means the increase in money each year remains the same.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        On computing the total amount over several years, notice:
                    </p>
                <p>

                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The same amount of interest is added each year.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               The total grows in a steady and predictable way.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The original amount remains the reference point throughout.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                    <p>
                        <term>Think about it:</term> Why does the total increase at a constant rate even after several years?
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Observing Changing Growth</term>
                </p>

                    <p>
                        In Plan B, the situation is different. Each year, the amount used for calculation changes because previous growth is included.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        On computation year by year, observe that:
                    </p>
                <p>

                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The increase becomes larger each year.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The base amount keeps changing after every cycle.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The growth starts slowly but accelerates over time.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                    <p>
                        <term>Think about it:</term> Why does the amount grow faster in later years compared to earlier years?
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Searching for a Pattern</term>
                </p>

                    <p>
                        What do you notice when comparing yearly values in Plan B.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Instead of adding a fixed amount, each new value is obtained by multiplying the previous amount by the same factor.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <term>Discuss in groups:</term>
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can we predict future values without calculating each year step by step?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What is the simplest way to describe repeated multiplication?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How does this pattern differ from simple addition growth?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>From Patterns to General Understanding</term>
                </p>
                    <p>
                        From these observations, we can describe financial growth  in two main ways:
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Steady growth based on a fixed reference value.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Accelerating growth based on repeated multiplication.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                    <p>
                        This prepares us to introduce formal methods for calculating interest, profit, and long-term financial changes.
                    </p>

                <p>
                    <term>Reflection</term>
                </p>

                    <p>
                        Consider real-life situations such as savings accounts, loans, and business investments.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <term>Reflect:</term>
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Why do different financial systems lead to different outcomes over time?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How can understanding patterns help individuals make better financial decisions?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>

                </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a youth SACCO in Kisumu, members save money to support small business projects. One group deposits Ksh <m>20,000</m> in an account that earns simple interest at a rate of <m>5\%</m> per year.
            </p>

            <p>
                Determine the total amount the group will have after <m>3</m> years.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Annual interest:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        I = \amp \; \frac{5}{100} \times 20,000 = 1,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Total interest for 3 years:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        1,000 \times 3 = 3,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Total amount:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        20,000 + 3,000 = 23,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A student uses a mobile savings app that rewards users with compound interest at a rate of <m>10\%</m> per year. The student invests Ksh <m>10,000</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Find the amount after <m>2</m> years.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Year 1:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        10,000 \times 1.1 = 11,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Year 2:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        11,000 \times 1.1 = 12,100
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Final amount = Ksh <m>12,100</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A learner buys a smartphone for Ksh <m>30,000</m>. The phone loses value at a rate of <m>20\%</m> per year due to wear and technology changes.
            </p>

            <p>
                Find its value after <m>2</m> years.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Year 1:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        30,000 \times 0.8 = 24,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Year 2:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        24,000 \times 0.8 = 19,200
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Final value = Ksh <m>19,200</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A family buys a television on hire purchase. The cash price is Ksh <m>24,000</m>. They pay a deposit of Ksh <m>6,000</m> and the balance is paid in <m>12</m> monthly instalments of Ksh <m>1,500</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Determine the total amount paid and comment on the cost.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Total instalments:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        12 \times 1,500 = 18,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Total amount paid:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                        18,000 + 6,000 = 24,000
                    </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                The total cost equals the cash price, meaning there is no extra cost in this simplified case.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A group saves Ksh <m>18,000</m> in a bank at <m>5\%</m> simple interest per year. Find the total interest after <m>3</m> years.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>2,700</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A mobile savings app gives <m>8\%</m> compound interest per year. If Ksh <m>15,000</m> is invested, find the amount after <m>2</m> years.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>17,496</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A laptop costs Ksh <m>50,000</m> and depreciates at <m>10\%</m> per year. Find its value after <m>2</m> years.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>40,500</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Matrix for Real Life Commercial Arithmetic applications</title>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>Struggling Learners (Support)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Provide highly structured step-by-step graphic organizers that separate baseline values from active interest pools. Focus on isolating annual arithmetic growth on its own before moving on to multi-year compound interest calculations.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Provide worksheets with pre-calculated multipliers (such as <m>1.10</m> or <m>0.80</m>) to minimize calculation errors and help learners focus on understanding structural growth patterns.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>On-Level Learners (Core)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Learners extract commercial variables independently, map growth behaviors, and solve problems involving hire purchase costs, linear savings patterns, and multi-tier reducing balance equations.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            They participate in small group discussions to compare financial alternatives and write algebraic growth models using standard variables (<m>P, R, T, n</m>).
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Extend problems to complex financial scenarios, such as finding the initial investment or principal amount given only the final accumulated value and compound interest parameters over time.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Task learners with analyzing real-world loan structures and comparing flat-rate interest charges against true reducing-balance options. They can also create original word problems based on local business scenarios for their classmates to solve.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

